Introduction to R Notebook

R Notebooks provide a powerful and flexible way to interactively develop and share your R code. They allow you to combine code, output, and narrative text in a single document, making them ideal for data analysis, exploration, and reporting.

. Getting Started with R Notebooks

1- Creating an R Notebook

  • Open RStudio.

  • Go to File > New File > R Notebook.

2- Structure of an R Notebook

  • An R Notebook consists of text chunks and code chunks.

  • Text chunks are written in Markdown.

  • Code chunks are written in R and are enclosed by triple back ticks with {r} at the beginning.

  • You can run the code chunks individually and see the output immediately below the chunk

Simple code block in R Notebook 
#This is a code chunk 
print("Hello")
[1] "Hello"
  • Follow this link for more information on R Markdown .

Pipes

Pipes %>% allow you to chain commands together, making your code more readable and efficient. The tidyverse package provides the pipe operator, and it is also included in the dplyr package.

Pipe operators : hsb2 data

  • Now that we are familiar with the hsb2 data, let’s use the pipe operator to make our code more efficient and avoid creating multiple data subsets.

  • The following code demonstrates how to use the pipe operator to mutate, remove a column, and rename variables in the dataset, applying all these changes efficiently in a single pipeline:

  • In this code:

  • mutate(new_column = some_transformation(existing_column)): Adds a new column by transforming an existing one.

  • select(-unwanted_column): Removes the specified column.

  • rename(new_name1 = old_name1, new_name2 = old_name2): Renames specified columns.

  • Using the pipe operator (%>%), all these operations are performed sequentially and the resulting dataset is assigned back to hsb2.

highschool <- read_csv("hsb2.csv") %>% 
  mutate(race = factor(race, levels = c(1,2,3,4),
                             labels = c("hispanic", 
                                        "asian", 
                                        "african-american", 
                                        "white")),
         ses = factor(ses, levels = c(1,2,3),
                           labels = c("low", 
                                      "middle", 
                                      "high")),
         schtyp = factor(schtyp, levels = c(1,2),
                           labels = c("public", 
                                      "private")),
         gender = factor(female, levels = c(0,1),
                           labels = c("male", 
                                      "female"))) %>% 
  select(-female) %>% 
  rename( socioeconomic_group = ses, 
          racial_group = race, 
          school_type = schtyp)

  • The following code provides a score_summary for females who are from public schools using the pipe operator to filter, summarize, and format the data:
Example

  • In this code

  • Filtering Data:filter(gender == "female", school_type == "public"): Selects rows where the gender column is “female” and the school_type column is “public”.

  • select(read:socst): Selects columns from read to socst. These columns typically represent different subjects such as reading, math, science, and social studies.

  • summarise_all(mean): Computes the mean (average) for each selected column. This operation calculates the average score for each subject across all female students in public schools.

  • After executing this code, score_summary will contain a single row of data with the average scores for reading, math, science, and social studies among female students attending public high schools.

score_summary <- highschool %>% 
  filter(gender == "female", school_type == "public") %>%
  select(read:socst) %>%
  summarise_all(mean)

score_summary
# A tibble: 1 × 5

  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl>
1  51.4  54.7  52.2    50.5  52.7

Handling Missing Data

Dealing with missing data is essential for maintaining data integrity. The tidyverse package offers several functions for this purpose.

  • In this course, we will use drop_na() and na.rm = TRUE for handling missing data, highlighting their differences:

  • drop_na(): Removes rows containing missing values (NA).

  • Typically used in data cleaning and preprocessing to exclude incomplete observations.

  • na.rm = TRUE:Used in functions like mean(), sum(), etc.

  • Computes statistics while ignoring missing values (NA).

  • Applied within specific functions to handle missing data during calculation.

Warning
  • drop_na() removes entire rows with any missing values, affecting the dataset’s structure.
  • `na.rm = TRUE is applied within functions to compute statistics on specific columns or variables without considering missing values.
    • drop_na() alters dataset dimensions by reducing the number of rows, while na.rm = TRUE affects only the calculation of specific summary statistics.

Understanding these distinctions is crucial for effectively managing missing data in data analysis and ensuring accurate results in statistical computations.

  • To demonstrate the effects of missing data using hsb2_missing_data.csv, you can illustrate how missing values impact data analysis and processing.
Example 
highschool <- read_csv("hsb2_missing_data.csv") %>%

Introducing ggplot2: Exploring Children Body Size Data

In this section, we will focus on the children_bodysize dataset and utilize ggplot2 to gain deeper insights into the data.

  • Load and manipulate the children_bodysize dataset using pipes and dplyr from the tidyverse, and then we will demonstrate various visualizations.

Loading and preparing the dataset

library(tidyverse)

# Load and preprocess the children_bodysize dataset
bodysize <- read_csv("children_bodysize.csv") %>%
  mutate(height = stature / 10,      # Convert stature to height (assuming stature is in cm)
         age = age / 12,             # Convert age to years (assuming age is in months)
         year_old = floor(age),     # Calculate age in whole years
         gender = factor(gender))   # Convert gender to factor for categorical plotting

Scatter Plot of Height vs. Age

plot(height~age, data=bodysize)

Basic Scatter Plot with ggplot2

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = bodysize, 
             mapping = aes(x=age, y=height, color=gender) )

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = bodysize, 
             mapping = aes(x=age, y=height, 
                           color=gender),
             size=0.5, 
             alpha=0.8)

Density Plot of Height by Gender for 15-Year-Olds

ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(data=filter(bodysize, year_old==15),
                 mapping = aes(x = height), 
                 binwidth=5)

ggplot() + 
  geom_density(data=filter(bodysize, year_old==15),
                 mapping = aes(x = height, color=gender))

Violin Plot of Height Distribution by Gender for 15-Year-Olds

ggplot() + 
  geom_violin(data=filter(bodysize, year_old==15),
                 mapping = aes(y = height, x=gender, color=gender, fill=gender))

Scatter Plot with Smoothed Line by Gender

ggplot(data = bodysize, 
       mapping = aes(x=age, y=height, color=gender)) +
  geom_point(size=0.1,alpha=0.8) +
  geom_smooth()
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Scatter Plot with Smoothed Line by Gender with Faceting

ggplot(data = bodysize, 
       mapping = aes(x=age, y=height)) +
  geom_point(size=0.1,alpha=0.8) +
  geom_smooth() + facet_wrap(~gender)
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Density Plot of Height by Gender Faceted by Age Group

ggplot(data = bodysize) +
  geom_density( mapping = aes(x = height, color=gender) ) +
  facet_wrap(~year_old)

  filter(age>=13, age<18) %>%
  ggplot() +

Jitter Plot of Foot Length by Age in Years

bodysize %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=year_old, y=foot_l)) +
  geom_jitter(size=.1)

These examples demonstrate how to effectively use ggplot2 for exploratory data analysis and visualization of the children_bodysize dataset. Adjust parameters such as binwidth, size, alpha, and facet_wrap as needed to refine your visualizations and gain insights into the data.
